Pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp} and the @ground turmeric{1%tsp}, stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{80%g} then chop into thirds. Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(stalks and all).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When the oil is hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> TIP: Drain off any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Once the mince is browned, add the @red Thai style paste{50%g}, @coconut milk{200%ml} and @water{50%ml}(for the curry), and stir to combine. Add the green beans, bring to the boil and then simmer until the sauce has reduced and the green beans are tender, ~{4-6%minutes}.

While everything finishes off, have a quick tidy up. Once cooked, taste the curry and add @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Divide the turmeric rice between #bowls{}, and top with the curry. Sprinkle on the coriander. Enjoy!